      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Italian immigrants arrived in massive numbers between 1880 and 1920 primarily to escape poverty, political instability, and heavy overcrowding in their home region. They moved to cities like Chicago, New York, and Philadelphia seeking factory work as industrialization rapidly grew in America. Their settlement transformed these urban neighborhoods into vibrant cultural hubs, often leading to clashes with local businesses but also fostering significant social change and economic diversity. Understanding this historical shift helps explain how diverse communities have shaped the modern American cityscape.",
